  • Description: The release was caused by an overfill during fuel delivery. Clean Harbors out of Tualatin, OR, were already onsite performing tank cleaning and will assist with the remediation of this release. They will recover the absorbent pads deployed by the Loves Personnel and then pressure wash the impacted area and recover the risen waters utilizing a vacuum truck. It was reported a nearby drain basin was impacted, but they were told it led to the onsite OWS unit. Clean Harbors estimates 100 gallons released impacting an approximate 75yd by 40yd area of asphalt and concrete.

  • Description: DESIGNATED RESPONDER (DR) RECEIVED A CALL REGARDING A LEAKING HAZARDOUS MATERIALS (HAZMAT) PACKAGE. DR RETRIEVED HAZMAT PACKAGE AND RETURNED TO THE PACKAGE SERVICE CENTER (PSC). item.title: Report E-2024070502
item.description:
Report E-2024070502

Identified by scraper @ 2024-07-25T15:13:18+00:00

  • Incident Date: 2024-07-15
  • City: PORTLAND
  • State: OR
  • Report Type: A hazardous material incident
  • Mode Of Transportation: Highway
  • Carrier/Reporter: R & L CARRIERS, INC.
  • Hazmat Fatalities: 0
  • Hazmat Injuries: 0
  • Non-Hazmat Fatalities: 0
  • Total Amount Of Damages: 5000
  • Serious Incident Ind: No
  • Description: On July 15, 2024, one (1) 5-gallon drum of UN1090 had faulty packaging and released approximately one and a half (1.5) gallons of product to the pallet and dock floor. R+L Carriers retained Cura Emergency Services, LC who dispatched a crew from GrayMar Environmental (GME) to remediate the impacted site. GME personnel deployed absorbents to the UN1090-impacted dock floor, pallet, and surrounding cargo. All spent absorbents were collected and containerized into one (1) 55-gallon drum, and the damaged 5-gallon pail was collected and containerized into one (1) 55-gallon drum for future transport and disposal.
